bio: [('Beginning', 'He began bowling in 2001 in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia. (Athlete, 14 Aug 2018)'), ('Awards', 'He received the Malaysian Universities Sports Council [MASUM] 2012 Sportsman Award. (themalaysianinsider.com, 02 Jun 2013)He won the National Higher Education Award in Malaysia for his bowling achievements in 2011 and 2012. (thestar.com.my, 15 Feb 2013)He was named the 2011/12 Federal Territories Sportsman of the Year. (fz.com, 04 Jan 2014)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralFAMILY FIRSTHe withdrew from the 2015 South East Asian Games in Singapore, when his wife, Noor Shafira Norasid, was due to give birth to his daughter Ayra Azzahra. "It was a difficult decision to pull out of the squad for the Games in Singapore, but it was my first child. I did not regret it." He went on to win gold in the men\'s doubles event at the following South East Asian Games in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, in 2017, and dedicated his medal to his wife and daughter. (nst.com.my, 21 Aug 2017)NATIONAL FIRSTHe became the first Malaysian tenpin bowler to win a World Cup title when he claimed victory at the 2012 edition in Wroclaw, Poland. The win was made more memorable as his luggage and bowling equipment had been lost on the way to the event, which meant he was forced to use rented bowling shoes and balls during the official practice. (thestar.com.my, 04 Jan 2014; azhamvosovic.blogspot.fr, 26 Mar 2013) '), ('Influence', 'His mother. (Athlete, 14 Aug 2018)'), ('Injuries', 'He broke his right collar bone in March 2016 after falling while cycling. He was sidelined for three months. name: MOHD AZIZULHASNI
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began cycling at age 10 in his hometown of Dungun, Malaysia. (puncakbikers.blogspot.com, 08 Aug 2012)'), ('Reason', 'He followed his brother to a cycling club, and used the bike given to him by his father as a reward for good exam results. "At 15 years old, I was determined to pursue cycling and left for Bukit Jalil Sports School. My parents were not too happy with my decision to become a sportsman because they wanted me to become a doctor but I was adamant with my dream of becoming a national champion in track cycling." (eurosport.yahoo.com, 07 Jun 2012; thestar.com.my, 26 Jun 2012; yayasansimedarby.com, 21 Mar 2016)'), ('Debut', '2007 (Athlete, 07 Mar 2012)'), ('Coach', 'John Beasley [national], AUS (thestar.com.my, 06 Jun 2018)'), ('Awards', "He received the 2017 Sportswriters Association of Malaysia Best Athlete Award. He won the same award in 2009. (thestar.com.my, 02 Mar 2018)In 2015 he received the Full Blue Award for sporting achievements from Victoria University, making him the first non-Australian to be given the award. (yayasansimedarby.com, 08 Mar 2016)He was named Terengganu Sportsman of the Year in 2010, 2011 and 2012. (astroawani.com, 25 Dec 2012)He was Malaysia's flag bearer at the opening ceremony of the 2008 Olympic Games in Beijing. (mncf.org.my, 27 Jul 2012; thepocketrocketman.blogspot.com, 01 May 2013)He was named Malaysian Sportsman of the Year in 2009 and 2010. (mncf.org.my, 27 Jul 2012; Facebook page, 06 Mar 2016)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTHe became the first Malaysian cyclist to win a medal at the Olympic Games when he finished third in the keirin at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. (cyclingnews.com, 17 Aug 2016; SportsDeskOnline, 29 Jul 2018) '), ('Influence', 'His wife and his family. (top10malaysia.com, 27 Jul 2012; Instagram profile, 03 Mar 2016)'), ('Nickname', 'Pocket Rocket Man, Jijoe (thepocketrocketman.blogspot.com, 01 May 2013; Facebook page, 06 Mar 2016)'), ('Injuries', 'A viral infection in his lungs forced him to withdraw from the individual sprint event at the 2018 Commonwealth Games in Gold Coast, QLD, Australia. He did compete in the keirin event at the Games. (nst.com.my, 05 Apr 2018)He withdrew from the 2016 World Championships in London, England, after falling ill due to a flu virus and tearing his thigh muscle in an accident during his training. (yayasansimedarby.com, 08 Mar 2016)In 2011 he dislocated his knee during an event in Indonesia. (uk.eurosport.yahoo.com, 07 Jun 2012)In February 2011 at the World Cup event in Manchester, England, his left calf was impaled by a shard of wood during a crash. He finished the race in third place before having the shard removed in hospital. The injury caused him to miss the world championships in Apeldoorn, Netherlands, the following month. (dailymail.co.uk, 23 Feb 2011; thestar.com.my, 26 Jun 2012; my.sports.yahoo.com, 19 Jun 2013)'), ('Education', 'Victoria University, Melbourne, VIC, AUS'), ('Languages', 'English, Malay'), name: ALIA SAZANA
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began shooting at age 15 at a range in Gong Badak, Malaysia. (thestar.com.my, 24 Sep 2012; nst.com.my, 05 Jun 2012)'), ('Debut', '2013 for Malaysia, World Cup in Munich, Germany (Athlete, 21 Aug 2018)'), ('Coach', 'Mohd Sabki Mohd Din [national], MAS; Park Sang-Soon [national], KOR; Park Cheol-Wan [national], KOR; Lee Dohee, KOR (sports247.my, 23 Aug 2017; thestar.com.my, 12 Sep 2017, 22 Feb 2017; sinarharian.com.my, 20 Aug 2017; Athlete, 21 Aug 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the Olympic Games. (thestar.com.my, 16 Feb 2018)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning a bronze medal in the 25m pistol event at the 2018 Commonwealth Games in Gold Coast, QLD, Australia and winning a gold medal in the same event at the 2017 South East Asian Games in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia. (thestar.com.my, 11 Apr 2018, 12 Sep 2017)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralENFORCED BREAKShe had to quit shooting in 2009 when she moved to Australia with her family. However, while visiting Malaysia the following year, she was drafted into the Terengganu team for the 2010 Sukma Games in Melaka, Malaysia, and won gold in the 25m pistol event. She moved back to Malaysia fully in 2011. "In Australia I wasn\'t able to shoot because I was not a citizen there and it was not easy to get a shooting license. Not being able to do something you\'re passionate about is really hard, I missed it so much. Then I came back and was asked to join the team. That reignited my career." (thestar.com.my, 16 Feb 2018, 14 May 2013) '), ('Hero', 'Malaysian shooters Bibiana Ng and Joseline Cheah, Malaysian squash player Nicol David, US basketball player Michael Jordan. (sinarharian.com.my, 11 Jul 2012; Athlete, 21 Aug 2018)'), ('Influence', 'Her parents and coach Lee Dohee. (thestar.com.my, 11 Apr 2018; Athlete, 21 Aug 2018)'), ('Nickname', 'Alex (Facebook profile, 05 May 2018)'), ('Injuries', 'She suffered an illness and lost 29kg in weight which kept her out for two months prior to the 2018 Commonwealth Games in Gold Coast, QLD, Australia. name: JUN HOONG
bio: [('Beginning', 'She took up diving at age nine. (thestar.com.my, 11 Aug 2016)'), ('Reason', 'Her father initially signed her up for swimming lessons at age four but at age nine diving coach Zhou Xiyang invited her to try diving. (thestar.com.my, 11 Aug 2016)'), ('Coach', 'Christian Brooker [national], AUS (thestar.com.my, 19 Apr 2018)'), ('Awards', 'She was nominated for the 2014 Malaysian Sportswoman of the Year award. (thestar.com.my, 29 Apr 2015)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTShe became Malaysia\'s first diving world champion when she claimed gold in the 10m platform at the 2017 World Championships in Budapest, Hungary. A year earlier, together with diving partner Pandelela Rinong, she won Malaysia\'s first Olympic synchronised diving medal, following their silver medal in the 10m synchronised platform event at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. This was also the first Olympic silver medal Malaysia had won in a women\'s event at the Games. (SportsDeskOnline, 29 Jul 2018; thestar.com.my, 20 Jul 2017, 29 Jun 2016; nst.com.my, 10 Aug 2016)CONTACTS IN COMPETITIONShe wears contact lenses when competing even though the chlorine in the pool is not good for them. "My vision is quite bad. It is easier for me with contact lenses as I can see what my coaches are signalling from the side when I\'m on the springboard or platform. I can\'t go for corrective eye laser treatments as I also have astigmatism [an eye condition causing blurred vision]." (nst.com.my, 01 Jan 2014) '), ('Injuries', 'She won a gold medal despite being troubled by back problems at the 2017 World Championships in Budapest, Hungary. (nst.com.my, 20 Jul 2017)She suffered a training injury in July 2015 that left her with damage to both her heels after getting too close to the springboard while performing a dive. The injuries ruled her out of the 2015 World Championships in Kazan, Russian Federation. She returned to competition in February 2016 at the World Cup event in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. (thestar.com.my, 18 Jul 2015; thestar.com.my, 11 Aug 2016)She considered retiring from the sport due an injury in 2009. (thestar.com.my, 11 Aug 2016)She sustained a back injury at the 2006 Commonwealth Games in Melbourne, VIC, Australia. The injury forced her to miss the 2006 Asian Games in Doha, Qatar. (The Star, 08 Feb 2007)She suffered a wrist injury in 2005. (RTM Olympics, 08 Feb 2007)'), ('Education', 'Communications - University Putra Malaysia, Serdang, MAS'), ('Languages', 'English'), ('Hobbies', 'Playing piano, singing. (thestar.com.my, 19 Apr 2018)'), ('Awards', "She was one of six athletes chosen to carry the Commonwealth Games Federation [CGF] flag at the opening ceremony of the 2014 Commonwealth Games in Glasgow, Scotland. An athlete was chosen from each region of the Commonwealth, and David represented the eight Asian nations competing at the Games. (bernama.com.my, 11 Jun 2014)She was named the Women's Squash Association [WSA] Player of the Year for six consecutive years between 2005 and 2010. She also won the award in 2012. (wsaworldtour.com, 2013; squashmagazine.com, 2012)She was inducted into the World Squash Federation Hall of Fame in November 2011, becoming the first active player to be receive the honour. (worldsquash.org, 10 Nov 2011)She was voted Malaysia's Sportswoman of the Year for the 10th time in 2014. (worldsquash.org, 10 Nov 2011; malaysiandigest.com, 29 Apr 2015)In 2008 she was presented with the Order of Merit by the king of Malaysia. (nicoldavidonline.com, 05 May 2009)She was one of the first entrants into Malaysia's SportExcel Hall of Fame in July 2002. (The Star, 09 Jul 2002)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTSShe became the first Malaysian squash player to win a gold medal at the Commonwealth Games when she claimed victory in singles at the 2010 Games in Delhi, India. She also became the first Malaysian squash player to win gold at the Asian Games when she placed first in singles at the 1998 Games in Bangkok. (SportsDeskOnline, 26 Jun 2018)OTHER ACTIVITIESIn December 2008 she set up an online social media news, blog and entertainment portal called Squash Stars. The purpose of the platform is to promote women squash players with the ultimate aim of promoting the sport for the Olympic Games. (Squash Stars Facebook page, 28 Oct 2017; paultan.org, 10 Jan 2018)TURNING POINTShe believes relocating to the Netherlands in 2003 to join up with Australian coach Liz Irving really launched her career. "The move to Amsterdam got me to go back a step and break everything down from scratch. I started from pretty much zero to build my technique and my movement and learn how to volley well. In the seniors it was a whole different ball game as opposed to being in the juniors. That was my turning point to be where I am right now." (nytimes.com, 18 Sep 2014) '), ('Hero', 'US basketball player Michael Jordan, Swiss tennis player Roger Federer. (princesquash.com, 29 Jan 2014; thestar.com.my, 16 Apr 2018)'), ('Influence', 'Her parents. (princesquash.com, 29 Jan 2014)'), ('Relatives', 'Her sisters Lianne and Cheryl have both played squash at national level in Malaysia. Her father represented the state of Penang in athletics, football and hockey. (nytimes.com, 18 Sep 2014; nurain4e.blogspot.com, 30 Sep 2013)'), ('Nickname', 'The Smiling Assassin (squashtalk.com 05 May 2009; issuu.com, 04 Feb 2015)'), ('Injuries', 'In early 2018 she suffered hamstring and adductor strain injuries, which caused her to miss the British Open in May that year. name: LIU YING
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began playing badminton at age 10, and started serious training at age 13 after she enrolled at Bukit Jalil Sports School [BJSS] in Kuala Lumpur. Malaysia. (star2.com, 10 Sep 2016)'), ('Reason', '"My dad encouraged me to take up the sport. But after I joined the Bukit Jalil Sports School [BJSS] I don\'t know why I stayed, as the programme was very tough. I just wanted to give myself a shot at the game. Though my father encouraged me, he never put pressure on me. I think that helped." (star2.com, 10 Sep 2016; gohliuying.org, 07 May 2016; bwfworldsuperseries.com, 10 Apr 2016)'), ('Debut', '2007 for Malaysia (bwfworldsuperseries.com, 10 Apr 2016)'), ('Coach', 'Pang Cheh Chang [national] (nst.com.my, 11 Jul 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a medal at a world championships. (travel3sixty.com, 28 Apr 2017)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning silver in the mixed doubles at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. (says.com, 19 Aug 2016)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTShe and partner Peng Soon Chan became the first ever Malaysian mixed doubles pairs to win a medal in the event at an Olympic Games, when they won silver at the 2016 Games in Rio de Janeiro. (SportsDeskOnline, 22 Jul 2018; says.com, 19 Aug 2016)INJURIES CAUSE CAREER RETHINKShe was unsure whether she would stay in the game after the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro, due to the injuries and surgery she has had on both knees. She says that every time she plays, her right knee swells and gives her pain. She manages this with medicine and the help of a physiotherapist. "I may retire. I have no plans after the [2016] Olympic Games. It all depends on the condition of my leg." In September 2016 she decided to continue playing. "Despite my injuries I\'m going to fight for badminton." (says.com, 19 Aug 2016; thestar.com.my, 31 Mar 2016, 06 Feb 2016)OTHER ACTIVITIESIn June 2017 she released a book named \'I am Goh Liu Ying\' about her life and career as a badminton player. "It\'s basically about my life as a shuttler and the ups and downs I have gone through. Hopefully, it will inspire another person." She also started an online t-shirt business as a joint venture with Malaysian women\'s doubles badminton player Lim Yin Loo. "The products depict a picture of a doll, which is me." (thestar.com.my, 24 Jun 2017) '), ('Hero', 'Swiss tennis player Roger Federer. (thestar.com.my, 11 Jul 2012)'), ('Injuries', 'In May 2017 she underwent right shoulder surgery in Halle, Germany, and returned to competition in November 2017 at the Indian International Series in Hydrebad. (bwfbadminton.com, 23 Nov 2017; thestar.com.my, 23 May 2017)She suffered an injury to her right hand at the 2017 India Super Series in New Delhi in April that year. Despite the injury she attended the 2017 Malaysia Super Series Premier in Kuching, the same month, but her and partner Peng Soon Chan were defeated in the first round which she attributed to her injured hand. (thestar.com.my, 07 Apr 2017)She has a history of knee problems dating back to 2008, and in early 2014, after first attempting traditional remedies, she entered a rehabilitation programme in an attempt to strengthen her knees. Her right knee was suffering from a meniscus tear and a partial ligament tear, while her left knee was suffering from a small meniscus tear. The rehabilitation forced her to miss two months of competition before returning for the Singapore Open in April 2014. She then underwent knee surgery on both her knees in May 2014, which kept her from competing in the 2014 Commonwealth Games in Glasgow, Scotland. She had further issues with her knee in January 2017 causing her to miss the Malaysian Masters in Sibu the same month, and resulting in restricted training. (thestar.com.my, 31 Jan 2017, 04 Jun 2014, 04 Feb 2014, 03 Jan 2014)In October 2016 she suffered an ankle injury at the Denmark Open in Odense. (thestar.com.my, 31 Jan 2017)She had a problem with her back during the Selangor Open in February 2012 and again at the All England Championships the following month where her mixed doubles team lost in the semifinals. (thestar.com.my, 11 Mar 2012; nst.com.my, 16 Mar 2012)'), ('Languages', 'Cantonese, English, Malay, Mandarin'), ('Hobbies', 'Swimming, reading, singing. bio: [('Beginning', 'He took up athletics in 2011. (thestar.com.my, 22 May 2015)'), ('Reason', 'His talent for running was discovered by scouts in primary school, and he was enrolled into the Tabuan Jaya Sports School in Kuching, Malaysia, where he competed first in football then athletics. "I was enrolled into the sports school and I took up football. I only got into athletics after I finished my first year of secondary school and started out in the 100m hurdles." (thestar.com.my, 22 Sep 2013)'), ('Coach', 'Zainal Abas [national] (stadiumastro.com, 29 Mar 2018; thestar.com.my, 01 Oct 2017)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralFROM ATHLETICS TO CYCLING AND BACKHe decided to switch from athletics to track cycling in late 2013, after first showing potential for cycling in a talent transfer programme in December 2012. After a year away from athletics he decided to switch back in December 2014 on the advice of fellow Sarawak-born sprinter Watson Nyambek. "As I was the smallest in class I never thought I could win gold at an Olympic Games competing in athletics, so switched to track cycling. But after I spoke to him [Watson] he believed that I had a good career ahead of me in athletics, so I wanted to thank him for believing in me. I want to be a great sprinter just like him." (thestar.com.my, 22 Sep 2013; 22 May 2015)PRESIDENTIAL NAMEHe was named \'Nixson\' after the 37th President of the United States of America, Richard Nixon. (thestar.com.my, 22 Sep 2013) '), ('Hero', 'Malaysian sprinter Watson Nyambek. name: CHONG WEI
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began playing badminton at age 11. (Facebook page, 25 Apr 2016)'), ('Reason', "He preferred playing basketball when he was younger, but his mother was not keen on him playing outside because it was so hot. Instead, his father introduced him to badminton and Lee soon attracted the attention of a local coach, who asked to take him on as a student. With his father's permission, Lee began training with the coach after school. (Facebook page, 25 Apr 2016; sport366.com, 13 Dec 2008)"), ('Coach', 'Datuk Misbun Sidek [national], MAS (thestar.com.my, 17 Apr 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a gold medal at the world championships. (scmp.com, 08 Mar 2017)'), ('Awards', "He was Malaysia's flag bearer during the opening ceremony of the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. (nst.com.my, 06 Aug 2016)He was named the Badminton World Federation's [BWF] Male Player of the Year in 2009, 2010, 2011 and 2013. (badmintonplanet.com, 26 May 2014; bwfbadminton.org, 12 Dec 2011)In 2008 he received the Darjah Setia Pangkuan Negeri [DSPN] from the state of Penang, Malaysia. The award allows him to carry the title of Datuk. (straitstimes.com, 12 Nov 2014)"), ('Additional Information', "GeneralSANCTIONHe tested positive for the banned substance dexamethasone at the 2014 World Championships in Copenhagen, Denmark. In April 2015 he was given an eight-month suspension by the Badminton World Federation [BWF], backdated to 30 August 2014. Lee claimed the substance had entered his system while he was receiving treatment for a thigh injury in July 2014. (olympictalk.nbcsports.com, 27 Apr 2015; olympictalk.nbcsports.com, 08 Nov 2014)NATIONAL FIRSTIn 2008 he became the first Malaysian badminton player to reach the men's singles final at the Olympic Games. His silver medal in Beijing was the first time a Malaysian athlete had stood on the Olympic podium in any sport since the 1996 Games in Atlanta. (howtobadminton.com, 17 Nov 2014; SportsDeskOnline, 03 May 2018)BIOPICIn March 2018 a biographical film about him titled 'Lee Chong Wei: Rise of the Legend' was released and premiered in front of over 20,000 people in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia. (thestar.com.my, 10 Mar 2018, 21 Dec 2017)BOOKIn 2012 he released an autobiography titled 'Dare to be a Champion'. (cliveworld.com, 06 Sep 2012) "), ('Hero', 'Chinese badminton player Sun Jun. (fourthofficial.com, 20 Aug 2015)'), ('Relatives', 'His wife Mew Choo Wong has also represented Malaysia in badminton, and competed at the 2008 Olympic Games in Beijing. (Facebook profile, 09 Mar 2018; SportsDeskOnline, 03 May 2018)'), ('Injuries', "In February 2017 he tore the medial collateral ligament in his left knee after slipping during a training session. He returned to competition in March that year. (hindustantimes.com, 12 Mar 2017; scmp.com, 08 Mar 2017)A thigh injury prevented him from competing at the 2014 Commonwealth Games in Glasgow, Scotland. (bbc.co.uk, 05 Jul 2014)In May 2012 he tore a tendon in his ankle during a Thomas Cup group match against Denmark in Wuhan, People's Republic of China. He spent two months on the sidelines. (thestar.com.my, 08 Nov 2013; thestar.com.my, 23 May 2012)In March 2012 he suffered a shoulder injury. (timesofindia.com, 30 Apr 2012)"), ('Languages', 'English, Hokkien, Malay, Mandarin'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationAsian Games2Singles2010Guangzhou, CHN3Singles2014Incheon, (themalaysiantimes.com.my, 23 Dec 2015)Together with her diving partner Pandelela Rinong, she received National Sports Awards in 2009 and 2013 for Best Female Team. (Facebook page, 10 May 2015)She was named Perak Sportswoman of the Year in Malaysia on four occasions between 1996 and 2009. (Facebook page, 10 May 2015)In 2007 she was presented with the Ahli Mahkota Perak [AMP] Honour by the Sultan of Perak in Malaysia. (thestar.com.my, 23 Apr 2007)She was named the 2001 Olympian of the Year by the Olympic Council of Malaysia. (Facebook page, 10 May 2015)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTSHer appearance at the 2012 Olympic Games in London made her the first female Malaysian athlete to have competed at four editions of the Games. She also represented Malaysia in 2000, 2004 and 2008. In 2002, together with Farah Begum Abdullah, she became the first female Malaysian diver to win a medal at the Asian Games. The pair claimed bronze in the 3m synchronised springboard in Busan, Republic of Korea. Then in 2009, she and her partner Pandelela Rinong became the first divers representing Malaysia to win a medal at the world championships, claiming bronze in the 10m synchronised platform event in Rome, Italy. (SportsDeskOnline, 29 Jul 2018; thestar.com.my, 05 Nov 2017; The Star, 21 Jul 2010, 10 Feb 2010, 08 Feb 2007) '), ('Hero', 'Chinese divers Fu Mingxia and Guo Jingjing. bio: [('Beginning', 'She began playing at age nine, and professionally at age 17. Her first coach when she took up squash was Lianne David, the sister of fellow Malaysian squash player Nicol David. "She was my first coach at age 10 when I was representing Penang at state level and Malaysia as a junior. Then I moved on to work with coach Aaron Soyza when I was 12." (nst.com.my, 18 Dec 2017; fourthofficial.com, 13 Feb 2017)'), ('Reason', 'She began squash lessons when her mother gave her a choice between squash and tennis. "I had two options, tennis or squash, and well, being a Malaysian, tennis wasn\'t the best option because of the weather, so I picked squash. But to be honest, I had no clue what it was." (fourthofficial.com, 13 Feb 2017)'), ('Coach', 'Peter Genever [national], GBR; Aaron Soyza [personal] (thestar.com.my, 01 Apr 2018; nst.com.my, 18 Dec 2017)'), ('Ambition', "To reach the top 10 rankings in singles again on the Professional Squash Association [PSA] World Tour, and to win a gold medal in the women's team event at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (nst.com.my, 18 Dec 2017)"), ('Awards', "In 2006 and 2008 she received the Hassan Musa Award for the Most Outstanding Junior Women's Performance from the Asian Squash Federation. (WISPA, 05 Aug 2010)"), ('Hero', 'Malaysian squash player Nicol David. (tocsquash.com, 22 Jan 2014)'), ('Influence', 'Her mother, and coach Aaron Soyza. (fourthofficial.com, 13 Feb 2017)'), ('Injuries', 'In March 2015 she suffered an anterior cruciate ligament [ACL] injury to her left knee which required surgery, and initially returned to competition in November 2015. By late 2016 a scan revealed that the initial graph in place on her ligament had disappeared, which meant she missed the whole of 2017 as she required another bout of surgery to reconstruct the ligament. She hoped to return for the 2018 Commonwealth Games in Gold Coast, QLD, Australia, but was unable to recover in time. She finally returned to competition after a 20-month lay-off at the 2018 Malaysian Open in July that year. (malaymail.com, 19 Jul 2018; thestar.com.my, 24 Feb 2018; nst.com.my, 18 Dec 2017)She suffered from dengue fever in 2014 but recovered in time to compete at the 2014 Commonwealth Games in Glasgow, Scotland. (theborneopost.com, 08 Aug 2014)In February 2014 she suffered a thigh injury at the Cleveland Classic event in the United States of America. (thestar.com.my, 23 Feb 2014)'), ('Languages', 'English'), ('Hobbies', 'Coffee, spending time at the beach. (psaworldtour.com, 17 Jul 2018)'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationAsian Games1Team2014Incheon, KOR1Team2010Guangzhou, CHN2Singles2014Incheon, KOR3Singles2010Guangzhou, CHNWorld Games4Singles2013Cali, COLWorld Championships5Singles2014Cairo, EGY5Singles2012Camana Bay, CAY5Singles2011Rotterdam, NED5Singles2010Sharm El Sheikh, EGY17Singles2015Kuala Lumpur, MAS17Singles2008Manchester, GBRWorld Team Championships2Team2014Niagara-on-the-Lake, ON, CAN3Team2012Nimes, FRA3Team2010Palmerston North, NZL3Team2008Cairo, EGYAsian Individual Championships1Team2008Kuwait2Singles2013Islamabad, PAK3Singles2011George Town, MAS3Team2010Chennai, INDWorld Ranking (as of 01 Aug 2018)70Singles2018')]

name: TZE LIANG
bio: [('Beginning', 'He took up the sport at age eight in Penang, Malaysia. (Athlete, 13 Aug 2018)'), ('Reason', '"My father asked if I wanted to \'play\' this sport called diving. Of course, when I heard the word \'play\' I got excited and said yes. At training, I suddenly realised my father\'s \'play\' meant jumping off springboards. I still remember how scary it was standing at the edge of the springboard for the very first time. It was the lowest springboard, but I was still scared." (sports247.my, 05 Dec 2012)'), ('Coach', 'Zhang Yukun [national], CHN (Athlete, 13 Aug 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win a medal at the Olympic Games. (Athlete, 13 Aug 2018)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning gold in the 3m springboard and silver in the 10m platform at the 2014 Commonwealth Games in Glasgow, Scotland. (Athlete, 13 Aug 2018)'), ('Awards', 'He was named the 2011 Best Sportsman at Bukit Jalil Sports School [BJSS] in Malaysia. (bjss-sportzbliz.blogspot.com, 14 Nov 2011)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTHe became the first Malaysian male diver to win a gold medal at the Commonwealth Games, following his victory in the 3m springboard event at the 2014 Commonwealth Games in Glasgow, Scotland. (SportsDeskOnline, 29 Jul 2018; buro247.my, 02 Aug 2016) '), ('Hero', 'His coach. (Athlete, 13 Aug 2018)'), ('Nickname', 'Davis (Athlete, 13 Aug 2018)'), ('Injuries', "He injured his right shoulder in July 2016 while training in the People's Republic of China. He returned to action in time to compete at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. (stadiumastro.com, 19 Aug 2016)He underwent surgery on his left shin in December 2015. name: NATASHA ANDREA
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began playing golf at age four. (The Star Malaysia, 08 Oct 2016)'), ('Coach', 'Steven Giuliano [personal], AUS (thestar.com.my, 04 Oct 2017)'), ('Ambition', 'To play professionally on the LPGA Tour. (Instagram profile, 13 Jul 2018)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralCOLLEGIATE CAREERIn December 2017 she accepted a scholarship to study and compete at San Jose State University in United States of America. She will begin her collegiate career following the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (pargolf.my, 20 Feb 2018; nst.com.my, 25 Dec 2017)PRO FRIENDShe has developed a friendship with US professional golfer Jessica Korda. Oon first met Korda at an LPGA Tour event in Malaysia in 2012. "She [Jessica] is such an inspiration to me, and I was glad that I got to meet her again. I was only 11 when I met her first and was delighted to see her again. When she\'s here I take her out to experience the local food." (The Star Malaysia, 08 Oct 2016)HOLE-IN-ONEAt age 12 she hit a hole-in-one at the 2014 Royal Selangor Golf Club [RSGC] Ladies Amateur Open Championship in Malaysia. She received a car for the hole-in-one despite not being old enough to drive. "I hit an 8-iron on the par three 120 yard hole, but duffed the shot. It hit the top of the hill and rolled. The first one to tell me that it was a hole-in-one was my mom. The insurance guy told my mom [about the car]. In 2016 my dad was still driving the same car." (The Star Malaysia, 08 Oct 2016; pga.com, 24 Aug 2014; LiveLifeDrive.com YouTube page, 22 Aug 2014) '), ('Hero', 'US professional golfer Jessica Korda. name: PANDELELA RINONG
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began diving at age eight in Kuching, Malaysia. (Athlete, 13 Aug 2018)'), ('Reason', '"I was picked by a swimming coach while she was on a visit to my primary school to look for potential swimmers to join her training programme. I was later given the choice to learn diving as I was not afraid of heights and was brave enough to jump from a three-metre board." (elle.my, 10 Aug 2016)'), ('Debut', '2007 for Malaysia, South East Asian Games in Nakhon Ratchasima, Thailand (Athlete, 13 Aug 2018)'), ('Coach', 'Zhang Yukun [national], CHN (Athlete, 13 Aug 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win gold at the Olympic Games. (Athlete, 13 Aug 2018)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning bronze in the 10m platform at the 2012 Olympic Games in London. (Athlete, 13 Aug 2018)'), ('Awards', "In 2017 the 'Pandelela Rinong Aquatic Centre' was opened to the public in Petra Jaya, Malaysia. (utusanborneo.com.my, 02 Mar 2017)In 2011 and 2013 she was named Best Sportswoman at Bukit Jalil Sports School [BJSS] in Malaysia. (theborneopost.com, 25 Nov 2013; thestar.com.my, 16 Nov 2011)She was flag bearer for Malaysia at the opening ceremony of the 2012 Olympic Games in London. (fina.org, 18 Mar 2016) She was named the 2009 and 2010 Sportswoman of the Year in Sarawak, Malaysia. (thestar.com.my, 15 Nov 2013)She was flag bearer for Malaysia at the 2010 Youth Olympic Games in Singapore. (thestar.com.my, 26 Aug 2010)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTSShe and her partner Leong Mun Yee became the first divers representing Malaysia to win a medal at the world championships, claiming bronze in the 10m synchronised platform event at the 2009 edition in Rome, Italy. She was also the first female Malaysian athlete in any sport to finish on the podium at the Olympic Games, taking bronze in the 10m platform event at the 2012 Games in London. (SportsDeskOnline, 29 Jul 2018; fina.org, 18 Mar 2016; theborneopost.com, 10 Aug 2012; Malay Mail, 30 Jul 2009) '), ('Hero', 'US diver David Boudia. (Athlete, 13 Aug 2018)'), ('Influence', 'Her father. (Athlete, 13 Aug 2018)'), ('Relatives', 'Her older brother Pardika Indoma has represented Malaysia in diving. He was ranked ninth in the 3m springboard synchro at the 2010 World Junior Championships in Tucson, AZ, United States of America. (SportsDeskOnline, 09 Aug 2017; e.nst.com.my, 31 Aug 2011)'), ('Nickname', 'Lela [given to her by her coach]. (Athlete, 13 Aug 2018)'), ('Injuries', 'She sustained a back injury during training at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. She skipped the synchronised 10m platform event and had to withdraw after the first round of the individual 10m platform due to the pain. (thestar.com.my, 30 Aug 2018; bernama.com, 30 Aug 2018)She suffered from back and shoulder problems from 2014 right the way through the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. (thestar.com.my, 24 Aug 2016)She suffered a knee injury in July 2014 that affected her participation at the 2014 Commonwealth Games in Glasgow, Scotland. The injury also meant she could only compete in two events at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea. (thestar.com.my, 06 Aug 2014; thestar.com.my, 29 Sep 2014)She suffered an ankle injury in 2012 after the Olympic Games in London that kept her out of the Asian championships and the ASEAN University Games. (nst.com.my, 03 Mar 2013)She suffered a shoulder injury in 2012. (Athlete, 13 Aug 2018)She sprained her ankle in 2011. (Athlete, 13 Aug 2018)She fractured a bone in her toe in 2010 that took six months to heal. (Athlete, 03 Jul 2012)She suffered from a lower back injury in 2008. name: JOO VEN
bio: [('Beginning', 'He took up the sport at age five but began training seriously at age 10. At age 11 has was selected to represent the state of Selangor before joining the junior ranks of the national team at age 13. (badminton-information.com, 25 Nov 2012)'), ('Reason', '"I began playing for fun when I was five years old at home. My parents always encouraged me to take up this sport." (bwfbadminton.com, 22 Apr 2018)'), ('Debut', '2014 for Malaysia (bwfbadminton.com, 22 Apr 2018)'), ('Coach', 'Datuk Misbun Sidek [national], MAS (thestar.com.my, 02 Jul 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (bwfbadminton.com, 22 Apr 2018)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning silver in the singles event at the 2012 Asian Junior Championships in Gimcheon, Republic of Korea, and being selected to compete at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia. (thestar.com.my, 02 Jul 2018; bwfbadminton.com, 22 Apr 2018; badminton-information.com, 25 Nov 2012)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL TEAMIn June 2018 the Badminton Association of Malaysia [BAM] announced plans to downsize the national squad. He said he has plans if he is dropped from the national team as a result of the restructuring. "All my teammates know about it [the restructuring] and we\'re not sure what\'s in store for us. If I\'m dropped, I\'ll become a professional and continue playing badminton like former internationals Liew Daren and Chong Wei Feng. I hope for the best but I\'m preparing for the worst too." In July 2018 he was called up by national coach Datuk Misbun Sidek to compete in the singles event at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia, as a replacement for ZulÂ\xadkarnain Zainuddin who was dropped for disciplinary issues. "I can\'t thank the coach enough. This is golden chance for me to revive my career after a series of recent disappointments." (thestar.com.my, 09 Jun 2018, 02 Jul 2018) '), ('Hero', 'Malaysian badminton player Lee Chong Wei, Chinese badminton player Lin Dan. bio: [('Beginning', 'She began paragliding in November 2014. (nst.com.my, 03 Feb 2015)'), ('Reason', '"Paragliding through the sky is really enjoyable, especially the fresh air.
